✅ 1. Class

A class is a blueprint or template used to create objects.
It defines properties (variables) and behaviors (methods).

🔹 Example:
WaterBottle class defines color, capacity, fill()

✅ 2. Object

An object is an instance of a class.
It represents a real-world entity.

🔹 Example:
A blue water bottle with 1L capacity is an object of class WaterBottle

✅ 3. Inheritance

Inheritance is the process where one class acquires properties and methods of another class.

Promotes code reuse

🔹 Example:
Thermos inherits from WaterBottle

✅ 4. Polymorphism

Polymorphism means one method behaves differently in different situations.

Types:

Compile-time (Overloading): Compile-time polymorphism is achieved when multiple methods have the same name but different parameters (number, type, or order).

Runtime (Overriding): Runtime polymorphism is when a child class provides a different implementation of a method defined in the parent class.

🔹 Example:
fill() works differently for normal bottle and thermos

✅ 5. Abstraction

Abstraction means hiding internal details and showing only essential features.

Achieved using abstract classes or interfaces

🔹 Example:
User only uses fill() without knowing internal working

✅ 6. Encapsulation

Encapsulation is wrapping data and methods together and restricting direct access to data.

Achieved using private variables + getters/setters

🔹 Example:
Capacity is accessed using setCapacity() and getCapacity()

✅ Short Summary (1-line each)

Class → Blueprint
Object → Instance of class
Inheritance → Acquiring properties from parent
Polymorphism → Same method, different behavior
Abstraction → Hide details, show only essentials
Encapsulation → Protect data using methods
